      <div xml:id="NA322-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu tōḻi ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu. 2. talaimakaḷ pāṅkikku uraittatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what the confidante said when [HE] was behind the fence. 2. It is also what SHE said to [her] friend.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA322">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            āṅkaṉan taṇikuva tāyiṉ yāṅku</l>
<l>            mitaṉiṟ koṭiyatu piṟitoṉ ṟillai</l>
<l>            vāykol vāḻi tōḻi vēyuyarn</l>
<l>            teṟintuceṟit taṉṉa piṇaṅkaril viṭarmukai</l>
<l>            yūṉṟiṉ piṇavi ṉuṭkupaci kaḷaiiya</l>
<l>            rāḷiyaṅ karumpuḻai yoṟṟi vāḷvarik</l>
<l>            kaṭuṅkaṇ vayappuli yoṭuṅku nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟaṇkamaḻ viyaṉmār puritiṉiṟ peṟātu</l>
<l>            naṉṉutaṟ pacanta paṭarmali yarunō</l>
<l>            yaṇaṅkeṉa vuṇarak kūṟi vēla</l>
<l>            ṉiṉṉiyaṅ kaṟaṅkap pāṭip</l>
<l>            paṉmalar citaṟiya paravuṟu palikkē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">If it decreases in that way, altogether</l>
<l>there is nothing else as cruel as this.</l>
<l>[Is it] true, oh friend?</l>
<l rend="indent2">– for<note place="foot">There seems to be no other way of construing than to take <term xml:lang="ta">palikku</term> as the indirect object of the <term xml:lang="ta">vāy-kol</term> sentence. The dative mark is slightly awkward in this connection. Perhaps one could argue in favour of a dative for a locative of topos ("concerning the offering, is it true (that it will take place)?"</note> the reverential offering when many flowers are scattered,</l>
<l rend="indent2">the spear-bearing [priest] singing while sweet instruments are sounding,</l>
<l rend="indent2">declaring so that it is realised</l>
<l rend="indent3">“a torment<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṇaṅku</term>: T.V.G. wants to take the poignant meaning of evil spirit here, but to me it also seems possible that the pain is simply declared to be a torment, a disease, that is, something that has to be cured, and then by implication it is still clear which kinds of remedies are on the priest’s mind.</note> [is this] severe pain abounding in affliction,”</l>
<l rend="indent4">from which the good forehead has become pale,</l>
<l rend="indent3">not obtaining in the suitable way the cool fragrant broad chest</l>
<l rend="indent">of the man from a land, where the fierce-eyed strong tiger with bright</l>
<l rend="indent">stripes is hidden, closing in on the forest-path difficult to move on for men,</l>
<l rend="indent2">in order to remove the dreadful hunger of [its] flesh-eating female</l>
<l rend="indent2">in a cave in the clefts in the thicket intertwining as if the bamboo</l>
<l rend="indent2">had grown high, been cut down [and then] packed close.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
